			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Wierd idea I have regarding mob camping...<a name="58812"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Aug 24 04 1:17 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>EQ2 raid content is apparently going to be instanced.  It is not going to lead to as much inflation as it first appears as a guild will still have to meet certain requirements in terms of quest trigger items or merely the passage of time to create the instance.  The difference between this and the current situation in most of EQ is that instead of one guild monopolizing a spawn and harvesting it every 3 or 7 days or whatever, now all guilds will individually do this.  I see both good and bad in it, in terms of the impact on game mechanics, but one thing is clear -- in terms of fairness, to have one guild consisting of people with more free time on their hands totally hogging a spawn is simply not fair to others who pay just as much for the right to experience the content.  This is a basic fairness issue - in a game which is not PvP to force groups of players to compete with one another in order to get the right to experience content is simply not fair, by Sony's own definition of their content.
<br />

<br />
At the same time, suppose we instance Rallos Zek and now all guilds capable of killing him can easily harvest two RZ's per week -- soon every warrior in every guild capable of killing him has a Blade of War.  Is this a good thing?  It could be argued that it is mudflation and spoils the game for everyone by trivializing content.  It could equally be argued that all this would do is speed up the inevitable.
<br />

<br />
Overall, I think there are more pros than cons to this approach, but I have never enjoyed racing other guilds to content - it promotes anti-social and aggressive behavior in a game I chose to play specifically to avoid those things.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
